share.share_text: White Otter Castleâ¦ Surrounded by natural beauty and steeped in legend, itâs truly a gem of the north that not many are able to experience. Jimmy McOuat constructed this three story log castle entirely on his own in the early 1900âs, at the age of 51, when there was no road access for hundreds of kilometres. Some of the red pine beams in the castle weighed up to 1600lbs, all painstaking hoisted into place. In 1918 Jimmy was found by local forest rangers, tangled in a fishing net, drowned at the bottom White Otter Lake near a reed bed, not too far from the castle. No one really knows what happened to him, but there are many rumours assuming the cause of death was not sheer accident. Now, his grave site lay next to the castle, and some say Jimmy still walks upon the grounds from time to time. If you look closely, you just might see him. @OntarioTravel #ontario_partner
